Intro - The Exploratory Data Analysis Cycle

Hi all! Welcome to our first live-coding session!

So, let’s get going! First things first: we need to get our tools out! Computer programmers call them “libraries”.

#This is our toolkit: The Tidyverse!
library(tidyverse)

#This library makes our graphs pretty.  There are many options.
library(ggthemes)
theme_set(theme_tufte()+theme(text=element_text(family="sans")))

The code above loaded the “tidyverse” package. Cool! But, we still need some actual data to work on.

exData <- read_csv("death penalty data.csv")

We’ve got data! But… now what? The awesome and terrifying answer is: it’s up to us! The process is called “Exploratory Data Analyis”, or EDA for short. It involves three stages:

  1. Ask questions about your dataset. What are you interested in? What varibles catch your eye? Are there relationships between variables? Find some summary statistics, make some visuals. Here, inspiration follows from perspiration - try things out! Play around and be creative!
  2. Analyze. What conclusions can you draw from your explorations? What could explain the qualities and trends that you see?
  3. Communicate. What results are worthy of sharing? How would you like your audience to engage with them? Should some sort of action be taken? What further study is needed?

Allright, let’s jump in. When I look at this data, it seems that age, sex, and race all deserve some attention.

Key Variables: Age, Sex, and Race

#Let's look at a histogram:
qplot(Age, bins=10, data=exData,
      main="Age of Executed Prisoners")

#And, let's see the stats:
summary(exData$Age)
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##   22.00   34.00   40.00   41.48   47.00   77.00

Ok, let’s summarize: prisoners tend to be about 40 years old when they’re executed. Note that we see right skew in the distribution: it’s more likely for older prisoners to be executed than younger prisoners. The middle 50% most “common” executions are of prisoners between the ages of 34 and 47.

Now, let’s take a look at the gender of executed prisoners.

#Let's look at a histogram:
qplot(Sex, fill=Sex, data=exData,
      main="Execution by Sex") + theme(legend.title = element_blank())

Woah, not many women. Let’s look at those numbers: there are 16 women out of 1442 total executions, so 1.10957% of all prisoners executed are women. I make two conclusions from this:

  1. Almost all executed prisoners are men.
  2. It’s going to be hard to draw conclusions about the women, since n=16 is a very small sample size.

In light of these observations, my intuition is to focus only on male prisoners. Finally, let’s look at race.

## Fancy Footwork Alert!  "Native American" is very long, messing up graphics
levels(exData$Race)[levels(exData$Race)=="Native American"] <- "N.A."

#Make a bar plot:
qplot(Race, fill=Race, data=exData,
      main = "Race of Excecuted Prisoners")

Looks like most of the prisoners were white, with black prisoners close behind. Does this mean it’s more likely for a white person to be executed? What issues might we be ignoring?

[waits for the audience]

That’s right, these are counts, not percentages! That’s important, because black Americans are only about 12% of the population. This dataset doesn’t contain information about US population and demographics for the years recorded, so we’d have to look at a different dataset if we wanted to follow-up on this.

Executions Over Time

######### ALERT:  Fancy Footwork Below!  Dont' stress about the details.


#Explain the date format to R
exData$Date <- as.Date(exData$Date, format="%m/%d/%Y")

#Add a "Year" column for easy reference
exData <- mutate(exData, Year = format(exData$Date, "%Y"))

#Shortcut to angle axis labels
angle_x_axis <- theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = -90)) 

#Count the total number of executions in each year
yearSummary <- exData %>% 
  group_by(Year) %>% 
  summarize(Total = n())

########## Fancy footwork is over!


qplot(Year, Total, group=1, geom="line", data=yearSummary,
      main="Executions Over Time") +
      angle_x_axis

Wow! This graph is teeming with narrative! What’s the story here? Why did executions build up to a crecendo in y2k, then taper off? Certainly there must be some event or policy change or … something?? We’ll need to look outside this dataset for the answers… but now we know what we’re looking for!

Executions by State

We have an idea about when executions are happening; what about where?

qplot(State, data=exData,
      main = "Executions By State")+
      angle_x_axis

Um… Damn, Texas. That’s one big phallic bar of death. Takeaways:

  1. The death penalty is really only an issue in a dozen or so states. Maybe we can take a closer look at those staes? Let’s take a look at the race distribution in each state:
dirtyDozen <- exData %>% 
  filter(State == "AL" | State == "AZ" | State == "FL" | 
         State == "GA" | State == "MO" | State == "OK" | 
         State == "VA" | State == "NC" | State == "OH" |
         State == "TX" | State == "AR" | State == "SC")

#deathStates$Race <- as.factor(deathStates$Race)     

dirtyRaceDist <- count(dirtyDozen, Method, State, Race) %>% 
        group_by(State) %>% 
        mutate(prop=n/sum(n))
  
qplot(State, prop, fill=Race, data=dirtyRaceDist, geom="col")

qplot(Race, geom="bar", data=dirtyDozen, fill=dirtyDozen$Race, 
      facets = ~dirtyDozen$State)+
      angle_x_axis+
      theme(legend.position = "none")

Lastly, let’s look at race over time:

qplot(Race, as.numeric(Year), geom="violin", data=exData, fill=Race)+
  coord_flip()

Some reactions:

  1. Again, this does not account for the racial distribution in the US; further data would be needed to scale the totals.
  2. Looks like Asian Americans only get executed in Oklahoma. What’s going on there?
  3. It looks like OK and AZ are the only states to execute Native Americans in any quantity. Not shocking.
  4. Again, since black americans are only about 12% of the population, they are highly overrepresented in executions!
  5. Why were so many Asian and Native Americans executed in the late 90s?
  6. Does the increase of exectutions of Latino prisoners in the early 2000s correspond to a demographic change? A policy or administration change?

Method of Exeution

First, let’s take a peek.

qplot(Method, geom="bar", data=exData, fill=Method)

Judging from the above, it looks like two methods are by far the most common: electrocution and lethal injection. Let’s take a look at them in more detail.

#Let's do electrocution first.  Let's filter:

electricExecutions <- exData %>% filter(Method == "Electrocution")

qplot(Race, data = electricExecutions, fill=Race,
      main="Death by Electrocution")

qplot(Year, data=electricExecutions,
      main="Death by Electrocution")+angle_x_axis

Observations:

  1. Looks like there’s almost parity between black and white prisoners who were electrocuted. Are black prisoners more likely to be electrocuted? We could do a little math to compare the proporiton here to the overall.

  2. It’s clear the electrocution was used mostly in the 80s and 90s, tapering off to just one a year in the 2000s and one total for the years after 2010. What factors contributed to its rise and decline? Legislation? Technology? Public attitudes?

#Let's do lethal injection next.  Let's filter:

injectedExecutions <- exData %>% filter(Method == "Lethal Injection")

qplot(Race, data = injectedExecutions, fill=Race,
      main="Death by Lethal Injection")

qplot(Year, data=injectedExecutions,
      main="Death by Lethal Injection")+angle_x_axis

It seems like a clear trend is emerging: as the US trended away from electrocution in the 90s, it transitioned to execution by lethal injection. I also notice that latino americans have been executed by lethal injection; what factors might contribute?

Let’s look at one more graph: a comparative boxplot for each method across time.

qplot(Method, as.numeric(Year), geom="violin", data=exData, fill=Method)+
  coord_flip()

Fascinating! Even though the firing squad is used less frequently than other methods (that’s one of the crazier sentences I’ve typed in an exploratory data analyis), it was used for the longest span of time relative to other methods. Eletrocution hit its heyday in 1990, but the transition to lethal injection by th early 2000s is clear. It’s possible that a regional subgroup analysis might show other interesting trends.

One last graph: let’s compare the the distribution of execution methods across states for our dirty dozen.

dirtyMethodDistro <- dirtyDozen %>%

Their Victims

One issue when analyzing the victims: this dataset is not entirely “tidy”, as info about multiple homocides has been condensed into a single column. We can fix this, but it’ll require a little more data wrangling (yee haw!) than we’re ready for right now.

For the moment, let’s focus only on single homocides.

singleHomo <- exData %>% filter(`Victim Count` == 1)


qplot(`Victim Sex`, data=singleHomo)

qplot(`Victim Race`, data=singleHomo, fill=`Victim Race`)

Observations:

  1. It seems that there’s a fairly equal gender split, overall, amongst the victims.
  2. There were 1081 total victims, and 842 of them were white; that’s 77.8908418% of single homocide victims who are white. This is very close to the proportion of whites in the US during the years in question. Eyeballing the other categories, it makes me suspect that race is not a factor when murderers select their victims. Of course, this is at the national level; almost certainly individual criminals have a broad range of motivations.

Conclusions and Recommendations

We’ve only scratched the surface of the dataset, but our preliminary observations have led us to a few conclusions and further questiosn:

  1. What happened in the year 2000 that changed the growing trend of exections?
  2. It seems that Black Americans are highly overrepresented in executions. If we could integrate demographic data across time and states, we’d be able to say more.
  3. What the hell is going on in Texas? It seems like an entirely seperate study would be needed.
  4. Oklahoma and Arizona stand out for executing native americans. What factors have contributed to this?
